    <li class="comment byuser comment-author-admin bypostauthor even depth-2" id="li-comment-8486">

        <div id="comment-8486">
        <article>
            <div class="gravatar">
                <img alt='Marco Schwartz' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/ff00bb813ba5f3567535b791f1487620?s=60&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D60&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-60 photo' height='60' width='60' />            </div>

            <!-- display the comment -->
            <div class='comment_content'>
                <header class="comment-header">
                    <cite class="author_name heading" itemprop="creator" itemscope="itemscope" itemtype="https://schema.org/Person" ><a href="http://www.marcoschwartz.com" ><cite class="comment_author_name" itemprop="name" >Marco Schwartz</cite></a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>                    
                    <!-- display the comment metadata like time and date-->
                        <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
                            <a href="http://www.openhomeautomation.net/control-a-relay-from-anywhere-using-the-raspberry-pi/#comment-8486">
                                <time  itemprop="commentTime" itemscope="itemscope" datetime="2013-05-29T17:23:59+00:00" >
                                    September 10, 2013 at 4:28 pm                                </time>
                            </a>
                        </div>
                </header>

                <!-- display the comment text -->
                <div class='comment_text entry-content-wrapper clearfix'  itemprop="commentText" >
                <p>You probably don&#8217;t have to use another transistor. I use the 2N2222 transistor a lot, and it supports 12V in this case without problems. The characteristics to look at are really the maximum collector current and power that the transistor can support (in this case 800 mA and 500 mW, so you&#8217;re probably safe).</p>
                                <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/control-a-relay-from-anywhere-using-the-raspberry-pi/?replytocom=8486#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-8486", "8486", "respond", "387")'>Reply</a>                </div>
            </div>

