                <p>Great write up!  I think this is what I need to make my project work, with some minor modifications.  Im trying to get my Pi to run a remote control that turns on remote sockets. <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Christmas-Etekcity%C2%AE-Wireless-Control-included/dp/B00FAII8T2/ref=sr_1_11?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1386446184&amp;sr=8-11&amp;keywords=Etekcity+5" title="Link to my system." rel="nofollow"></p>
<p>The remote has a 12V battery for a power supply, because of this I need to run a relay to simulate a button press on the remote but separate the power from the Pi.</p>
<p>My idea came from this write up<br />
</a><a href="http://www.instructables.com/id/Raspberry-Pi-GPIO-home-automation/" title="LINK" rel="nofollow"><br />
however the remote used in the project was not 12V thus leaving me stranded, and searching for a solution. I found someone who used a relay to simulate  a button press on separate project which lead me to search for a way to control a relay with the Pi. This would protect my Pi, and send the correct amount of power to the remote.</p>
<p>My question to you is how would you modify you schematic so that the Pi turns on the relay, and the power is then sent where it needs to go?</p>
<p>Any help is greatly appreciated!</p>
<p>Keep up the great work!</p>
<p>~Carlos</a></p>
